Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell["Introduction", "Section",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.9838521280935917`*^9, 
  3.983852131112509*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"eb341f88-df98-4d6a-94f3-\
131f2ed56e23"],

Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell["\<\
In the geometric optics regime, the GW wavelength is assumed to be much \
smaller than the Schwarzschild radius of the lens. In this limit, \
gravitational waves propagate along null geodesics of the background \
spacetime, and the transverse tensor polarizations (plus and cross) remain \
unchanged apart from parallel transport along the geodesics.\
\>", "Item",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.9838521355594435`*^9, 3.983852174433503*^9}, 
   3.983852329184538*^9, {3.9838548183109493`*^9, 
   3.9838548332776737`*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"c4f10c56-6e45-4ad6-b419-\
6e6e1ddc11ba"],

Cell["\<\
Within the geometric optics approximation, the detection of additional GW \
polarizations is often interpreted as evidence for physics beyond GR. \
However, this approximation breaks down for many realistic astrophysical \
scenarios. Inclusion of wave effects such as diffraction and scattering can \
modify the polarization content, potentially leading to effective scalar or \
vector polarization modes even within GR.\
\>", "Item",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.9838521355594435`*^9, 3.983852174433503*^9}, 
   3.983852329184538*^9, {3.9838548183109493`*^9, 
   3.9838548381577835`*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"f612a085-ba0c-4d04-b645-\
fac807692c99"],

Cell["\<\
The non-tensorial polarizations arise from the coupling of the standard \
tensorial modes produced at emission with the curvature of the background (in \
presence of the lens). \
\>", "Item",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.9838521355594435`*^9, 3.983852174433503*^9}, 
   3.983852329184538*^9, {3.9838548183109493`*^9, 
   3.9838548375915127`*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"e6163f79-b0cb-4c22-bf8e-\
be9d7c1df8a0"]
}, Open  ]]
}, Open  ]],

